		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top">
		    <p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <BLockquote>
<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/057257.html">A Friendly Word for Gordon</a></B><P>

This is my first time posting to these message boards, though I read them frequently, especially the responses you make, Abashi. ;)<P>

I want to start off by saying that I do not always agree with you, but neither do I consistently find myself cursing your name after reading your posts. Most of the time I find you to be eloquent and professional. <P>

While you do unfailingly represent your employers concerns, you do give your words (whether they're what we want to hear or not) a touch of humanity that is noted and much appreciated. It reminds us all that we are not dealing with a faceless entity here. You are a person, just like the rest of us. Simply because it is your job to deal with us does not mean we have the right to treat you like a dog.<P>

I see so many posts on these boards that were obviously contrived by children or adults who never grew up. It is truly disheartening to see so much anger and malice unduly directed at you, Gordon. Regardless of the fact that you make mistakes from time to time, regardless of the fact that you don't always answer, regardless of the fact that when you do answer we may not like it, you are one of us. Just as we are allowed mistakes, so are you. So many people expect you to be perfect, to give them all the answers that they want and then to drift out of sight without a word of thanks... :( ...I just don't understand how people can treat a fellow human being that way.
<P>

You have one of the most difficult and stressful jobs in the world, not because Verant has a particularly excessive customer service workload (compared to other companies in other fields), but because you work in Public Relations. Everything you say has to be said with a smile regardless of how asinine and belligerent your customers are. I could never do you job, Friend. I would be jailed for murder after the first day. :) 

Well, this "word" has grown far longer than I intended it. I just wanted you to know that there are some people out here who, though we may not always see issues the same way, understand and sympathize with the stress you are under, and what exactly your job entails.<P>

I wish you Luck and Good Tidings...<P>

Farewell<P>

<B>Thanks Alena, I appreciate the note. I do envision a day where I can spend more of my time replying to posts such as these, or at least threads of respectful disagreement :)<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/059032.html">I think I see the source of Verant's problems...</a></B><P>

Now Abashi has stated that rogues are "the necromancers of melee" and later clarified that he means that they are on the upper end of the balance scale, which would seem to indicate that he considers necromancers to be nearly perfectly balanced<P>

<B>Actually, no. I would consider necromancers to be "on the virge of being overpowered". By "overpowered" I do not speak of pure offensive power, but everything that makes up a class that figures into the balance equation. "Perfectly balanced" lies somewhere between "overpowered" and "underpowered" in this sense.<P> 

By saying that rogues are the "necros of melee", I was not speaking of versitility nor solo capability, but rather that rogues are on the virge of being overpowered every bit as much as necros are. The original vision for rogues was more of a "thief" than they are now. However inability to fully implement some of the skills we had planned (sense/disarm traps), we decided to fit them more into an "assassin" role. </B><P>

Now since they could not fit Verant's niche monks invented a new, valuable and effective niche for themselves and became EQ's master pullers, bringing themselves back into balance with the EQ's environment<P>

<B>I've taken quite a bit of heat from some players about some comments that I made about not liking feign-pulling. Quite simply, when feign-pulling, a monk uses a skill that we created for something other than its purpose. Feign Death was supposed to be an escape skill, not a skill that allowed easier breaking of camps. Also consider that feign-pulling doesn't make sense from a roleplay perspective (we like it when things make sense in this fashion). Can you see a creature saying, "I'M MAD AT HIM, I'M GOING TO KI...wait... he's dead now.. I guess I'll go ba...AH HA! HE'S NOT DEAD, I'M GOING TO KI...wait...no... dead again....(ad nauseam)" </B><P>

Verant needs to realize that they have not created the perfect gaming environment, and therefore need to alter their perception of some of the classes and bring them in line with the world they have created, not the world they had envisioned. <P>

<B>We're well aware that the game isn't perfect. Afterall, what game can be? That said, what good would we do as game designers if we did not have some idea for the way we wanted the game. People will continue to make the decision as to whether the game we offer is one that they are willing to play.<P> 

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/059064.html">Abashi - Still no word on Fleshy Orb?</a></B><P>

About a week ago in that thread, you asked us players concerned with the Fleshy Orb quest to email you with details and the problems we're facing with it. <P>

I and a few players sent emails to your address at gwrinn@verant.com and all we got as a response is your autoresponder message. I and the players would like to know whether this is being looked into. I'm too tired to express my displeasure this time. Let's see whether a *nice* message like this works.<P>

<B>I do thank everyone for sending the notes that I requested. We were able to find the issue that caused the *latest* failure of this quest to work, a change that should hopefully go in sometime next week. Just to be safe however, I think I'll avoid annoucing that it works again until it's on the live servers.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/059066.html">Abashi please tell me I am wrong about this - hybrid experience penalty</a></B><P>

So, therefore, a hybrid who has to make more experience in the first place for the same lvl also loses more experience when he dies.
<BR>Tell me my logic is flawed Abashi<P>

<B>It's flawed :)<P>

Everyone of a given level loses the same amount (numerically) of experience at death. As a percentage of total experience, the race/class combos that require less experience to level lose comparativly move experience on death than those who take more to level.<P>

-Gordon</B>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
